<subSubSection id="BDF56CA31804FFDF378DFC0FFDAEFB25" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="F5503F281804FFDF378DFC0FFDAEFB25" blockId="9.[151,1437,151,1184]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
<emphasis id="C79BE33A1804FFDF378DFC0FFEA9FB95" bold="true" box="[199,335,1015,1040]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Comments.</emphasis>
The distinctive and contrasting colours, with the head, most of the thorax and male postabdomen yellow in contrast with the dark preabdomen and katatergite, render this species unmistakable. 
<taxonomicName id="32EF44AB1804FFDF33F5FBE4FA64FBB1" box="[1215,1410,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Howickia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis id="C79BE33A1804FFDF33F5FBE4FA64FBB1" box="[1215,1410,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Howickia bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the Hen and Chicken Islands, east of the North Auckland Peninsula, 
<number id="43272D0F1804FFDF3338FBB8FB68FBDD" box="[1138,1166,1088,1112]" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" value="40.0">40</number>
kilometers southeast of Whangarei. Only one female was dissected, and the apical abdominal sclerites are minute, pale and compact, with individual sclerites difficult to discern.
</paragraph>
